# CSE Student Question Intent Dataset (v0.1)

**Last updated:** 2026-03-10  
**Dataset type:** Student-written short questions for *intent detection* (multi-class text classification).  
**Collection method:** Google Form (self-submitted by undergraduate CSE students).  
**Current size (after cleaning/dedup):** **3,838** question instances from **44** respondents.

---

## Dataset summary

This dataset contains questions written by undergraduate CSE students (1st–4th year). Each question is associated with one **intent label** (20 intents) and a **language tag** (English, Bangla, or Mixed). The dataset is designed to support research on **question intent detection** in an academic/student-help context.

---

## Supported tasks

- **Intent Detection / Intent Classification** (single-label, 20 classes)
- Optional analyses:
  - Performance by **year level**
  - Performance by **language type** (en/bn/mixed)

---

## Languages

- `en` (English)
- `bn` (Bangla)
- `mixed` (Bangla-English mixed / code-mixed)

Current distribution (cleaned):
- English (`en`): **1,414**
- Mixed (`mixed`): **1,504**
- Bangla (`bn`): **920**

---

## Label set (20 intents)

- 1. Debugging / Error Fixing
- 2. How-to Implementation
- 3. Concept Explanation / Clarification
- 4. Algorithm Choice / Strategy
- 5. Data Structures
- 6. Time & Space Complexity
- 7. Programming Language Syntax / Features
- 8. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)
- 9. Database / SQL
- 10. Operating Systems (OS)
- 11. Computer Networks
- 12. Web Development
- 13. Software Engineering / SDLC
- 14. Machine Learning / AI
- 15. Cybersecurity
- 16. Competitive Programming / Problem Solving
- 17. Project Guidance / System Architecture
- 18. Tooling / Environment Setup
- 19. Career / Internship / Interview Prep
- 20. Exam / Assignment / Course Admin

---

## Data fields (CSV schema)

The released CSV file is in **long format** (1 row = 1 question):

| Column | Type | Description |
|---|---|---|
| `question_id` | string | Unique ID (e.g., Q000123) |
| `respondent_id` | int | Anonymous respondent index (1..N in the current file) |
| `timestamp` | datetime | Form submission timestamp (as provided in the sheet) |
| `year` | int | Student year (1/2/3/4) |
| `intent_id` | int | Intent ID (1..20) |
| `intent` | string | Intent name |
| `language` | string | `en` / `bn` / `mixed` |
| `text` | string | The question text |

---

## Cleaning and quality control

**Performed in v0.1:**
- Removed empty entries and obvious non-answers (e.g., “yes/no/null”, very short fragments).
- Split multi-line entries into separate questions when users wrote multiple questions in one box.
- Basic PII redaction:
  - Emails → `[REDACTED_EMAIL]`
  - Phone-like patterns → `[REDACTED_PHONE]`
- Exact deduplication **within** `(intent_id, language, normalized_text)`.

**Not yet fully handled (future versions):**
- Near-duplicate detection (paraphrases).
- Manual verification of student-selected intent labels (label noise estimation).
- Advanced PII removal (names, IDs) if present inside text.

---

## Current dataset composition

- **Respondents:** 44
- **Questions (cleaned):** 3,838

Year distribution (cleaned):
- Year 1: **2,021**
- Year 2: **685**
- Year 3: **1,132**
- Year 4: **0** *(currently missing / not collected yet)*

---

## Recommended splits for modeling

To avoid label imbalance and make results comparable:
- Use **stratified split** by `intent_id` (e.g., 80/10/10).
- Report **Macro-F1** + per-class Precision/Recall.
- Also report performance by:
  - language (`en`, `bn`, `mixed`)
  - year (1/2/3/4) once year-4 data exists

---

## Intended use

- Training and evaluating intent detection models for:
  - student Q&A assistants
  - academic helpdesk/chatbots
  - educational NLP research (code-mixed + student domain)

---

## Limitations and bias notes

- **Selection bias:** Volunteers submitting via Google Form; may not represent all students.
- **Label noise:** Students choose intents; some questions may be miscategorized.
- **Year imbalance:** Year-4 data is currently absent in v0.1.
- **Domain bias:** CSE-centric topics; generalization to other domains may be limited.

